I'm testing by asp.net core ( microsoft/dotnet:2.0.3-sdk ), when I get the method of stacktrace, there is a problem;

result of running on windows:

```
GetParentMethod    |    <GetOfController>b__2_0    |    InnerInvoke    |    Run    |    ExecuteWithThreadLocal    |    Dispatch
```



result of running on ubuntu16.04:
```
GetParentMethod    |    InnerInvoke    |    Run    |    ExecuteWithThreadLocal    |    Dispatch
```

where is the `"<GetOfController>b__2_0"` ?


***********source**********

Controller:
```
[HttpGet]
public Task<string> GetOfController()
{
    return Task.Run(() =>
    {
        return _testService.GetParentMethod();
    });
}
```

TestService:
```
public string GetParentMethod()
{
    StackTrace stack = new StackTrace();
    var frames = stack.GetFrames();
    return string.Join("  |  ", frames.Select(o => o.GetMethod().Name)); ;
}
```

The [ASP.NET Core 2.1 Roadmap](https://blogs.msdn.microsoft.com/webdev/2018/02/02/asp-net-core-2-1-roadmap/#mvc) mentions placing `[BindProperty]` on a controller class will bind all properties in the controller. This is not the case.

For example, with
``` c#
public class VController : Controller
{
    [BindProperty(SupportsGet = false)]
    public string FirstName { get; set; } = "John";

    [BindProperty(SupportsGet = false)]
    public string LastName { get; set; } = "Smith";

    // ...
}
```
both `FirstName` and `LastName` are model bound. With
``` c#
[BindProperty(SupportsGet = false)]
public class VController : Controller
{
    public string FirstName { get; set; } = "John";

    public string LastName { get; set; } = "Smith";

    // ...
}
```
neither property is bound.

Change `Startup.ConfigureServices` to include
``` c#
            services
                .AddMvc()
                .SetCompatibilityVersion(CompatibilityVersion.Version_2_0)
                .AddRazorPagesOptions(options =>
                {
                    options.AllowAreas = false;
                });
```

Expected: All area-related pages result in 404s.
Actual: See the usual content of pages such as https://localhost:44312/Identity/Account/Manage or https://localhost:44312/MyArea

Note either `CompatibilityVersion.Version_2_0` or `AllowAreas == false` should have been sufficient to disable areas.

Change `Startup.ConfigureServices(...)` to include
``` c#
            services
                .AddMvc()
                .SetCompatibilityVersion(CompatibilityVersion.Version_2_1)
                .AddRazorPagesOptions(options =>
                {
                    options.AreaRootDirectory = "/";
                    options.RootDirectory = "/";
                });
```

Expected: At worst, some confusing between area-specific and non-area pages. 
Actual: 404s for all pages, even full paths such as https://localhost:44312/About.cshtml or https://localhost:44312/MyArea/Index.cshtml

For PowerBI access token we need AAD Access Code.
For the time being workaround is to implement OpenId provider and extract code in OnAuthorizationCodereceived like this:

```
public AzureADOpenIdConnectOptionsSetup(IOptionsMonitor<AzureAdOptions> azureADOptions, 
 DataProtectionProvider dataProtectionProvider, 
                IConfiguration cfg, PowerBIAuthService pbi)
            {
                _dataProtectionProvider = dataProtectionProvider;

                CurrentValue = new OpenIdConnectOptions
                {
                    ClientId = azureADOptions.CurrentValue.ClientId,
                    Authority = $"{azureADOptions.CurrentValue.Instance}{azureADOptions.CurrentValue.TenantId}",
                    CallbackPath = azureADOptions.CurrentValue.CallbackPath,
                    Resource = cfg.GetValue<string>("PBI:PowerBiAPI"),
                    ResponseType = OpenIdConnectResponseType.CodeIdToken,
                    // TokenValidationParameters = new Microsoft.IdentityModel.Tokens.TokenValidationParameters { RoleClaimType = "roles" },
                    
                    Events = new OpenIdConnectEvents
                    {
                        OnAuthorizationCodeReceived = async ctx =>
                        {
                            var request = ctx.HttpContext.Request;
                            ctx.Options.ClientSecret = cfg.GetValue<string>("PBI:ClientSecret");
                            var currentUri = UriHelper.BuildAbsolute(request.Scheme, request.Host, request.PathBase, request.Path);
                            var credential = new ClientCredential(ctx.Options.ClientId, ctx.Options.ClientSecret);

                            var distributedCache = ctx.HttpContext.RequestServices.GetRequiredService<IDistributedCache>();
                            string userId = ctx.Principal.FindFirst("http://schemas.microsoft.com/identity/claims/objectidentifier").Value;

                            var cache = new AdalDistributedTokenCache(distributedCache, userId);
                            
                            var authContext = new AuthenticationContext(ctx.Options.Authority, cache);

                            var result = await authContext.AcquireTokenByAuthorizationCodeAsync(
                                ctx.ProtocolMessage.Code, new Uri(currentUri), credential, ctx.Options.Resource);

                            pbi.AADCode = ctx.ProtocolMessage.Code;
                            var its = cache.ReadItems();
                            ctx.HandleCodeRedemption(result.AccessToken, result.IdToken);
                        }
                    }
                };
            }

```
How to get the ctx.ProtocolMessage.Code from standard AAD provider?

